@node "Introtext" "Introduction"

Introduction

Welcome to InterTalk, the telecommunications package for the Amiga. 
Thank you for buying an InterActivision product. Once you have learned
how to use it, it will prove to be a flexible and powerful tool, and one
which we hope you'll want to keep on using for a long time to come.
With the aid of InterTalk and a modem you now have access to a worldwide
network of telecommunication organisations.
 
WHAT IS A TELECOMMUNICATIONS PACKAGE?

The word telecommunications, when used in conjunction with computers, is
the ability to talk to other computers via a modem and telephone lines.
With InterTalk you will able to connect your computer to services across
the globe and use the facilities which these services offer.  These 
facilities can be anything from sending and receiving messages (called 
Electronic Mail or EMAIL), sending or receiving files (called Binary Mail 
or BINMAIL) to playing games with other people around world (called 
Terminal Games, Multi User Games or MUGS).
@endnode


@NODE "APPENDIX A" "Menu summary"

MENU SUMMARY

The following pages list the function of all menu options, and where
appropriate, keyboard shortcuts in brackets.

PROJECT MENU
   This menu contains options relating to then loading and saving of your
   settings, the capture of data as it's received by InterTalk and access 
   to the FastMenu.

FASTMENU (Lightning bolt icon) - The opens up the FastMenu window which 
   allows you to change any of InterTalks settings.

   See Beginners Tutorial - Using InterTalk, The FastMenu for a more
   detailed description of the FastMenu.

DISK OPERATIONS (Disk icon) - The opens up the Disk Operations, it
   has all the features of Read Settings with exception that none of 
   InterTalk's information is saved, this option is purely for disk 
   management purposes.

   See Beginners Tutorial - Disk Operations for a more detailed
   description of the FastMenu.

CAPTURE FILE (Camera icon) - Select and activate a Capture File.
   To deactivate file capture reselect this item (or the icon). The 
   function is shown to be active via a tick to the left of this menu
   item and asterisk (`*') to the left of the `C' in the Quick Status
   Box.
   See Beginners Tutorial - Capturing Data from your screen, File
   Capture for a more information on capture files.

PRINTER (Printer icon) - When the option is activated all terminal
   data (not file uploads or downloads) will be sent to the printer
   for hardcopy output. An asterisk (`*') before the `P' in the Quick 
   Status Box or a tick to the left of the menu item denotes that 
   printing is active.
   See Beginners Tutorial - Capturing Data from your screen, Printer
   Capture for a more information on capture files.

READ SETTINGS (Amiga/O) - This option allows you to load a new
   settings file which has been stored on disk. The default settings
   file `InterTalk.CFG' is automatically read by InterTalk when the
   program starts.

SAVE SETTINGS (Amiga/S) - This option allows you to save your current 
   file onto disk for future use. The file `InterTalk.CFG' is read by 
   InterTalk at startup, therefore saving you settings to this file cause
   set InterTalk's default parameters.

ABOUT INTERTALK (Amiga/?) - Naturally, this option tells you a little
   about the program and its copyright holders. 

QUIT INTERTALK (Amiga/Q) - Allows you to Quit the program, freeing up
   any memory that it occupied.

EDIT MENU
   The Edit Menu contains options primarily concerned with the interchange
   of data between InterTalk and the Amiga's clipboard device and the 
   set-up of your modem commands and return strings.

CUT TO CLIPBOARD (scissors icon) - Cut the contents of the Scrollback 
   Buffer out and send it to the clipboard device for later use by 
   another program such as InterWord. Please note that the contents 
   of the Scrollback buffer are deleted after the use of this function.
   See Advanced Tutorial - The Clipboard, Transferring to and from
   InterTalk for more information on this feature.

PASTE CLIPBOARD (spray can icon) - Paste the contents of the Amiga's 
   clipboard device into the Terminal Window. This acts as if you 
   actually typed in the data. 
   See Advanced Tutorial - The Clipboard, Transferring to and from
   InterTalk for more information on this feature.

VIEW SCROLLBACK - Open the Scrollback Window, this contains, for your 
   perusal, the contents of the scrollback buffer (any recent Terminal 
   Window activity). The Scrollback Buffer currently has a fxied size 
   of 8Kb (8192 characters). In the next release of the InterTalk the 
   size of the Scrollback Buffer will be adjustable.

The following four menu items allow you to modify the modem commands
used for dialling, hanging up the phone line and getting the modems
attention.

DIAL-UP PREFIX - Edit the Dial-Up prefixed used by InterTalk to send a 
   dial command to your modem.
   Default: `ATDT'

DIAL-UP SUFFIX - Edit the Dial-Up suffix used by InterTalk to conclude a 
   dial command.
   Default: `\'
   See Appendix B - The Keyboard, Special Character Codes for a
   description special character which InterTalk supports within its
   strings.

HANG-UP STRING - Edit the command used to inform your modem to `hang up' 
   the phone line.
   Default: `ATH\' 
   See Appendix B - The Keyboard, Special Character Codes for a
   description special character which InterTalk supports within its
   strings.

ATT STRING - Edit the 'Attention' string required by your modem.
   Default: `+++'
   Please note that these are not special InterTalk characters, but the
   actual Attention command used by Hayes compatible modems.

MODEM STRINGS - This sub-menu contains nine items which, inform
   InterTalk of the strings the modem will send to it in certain 
   circumstances. NO DIALTONE - The string used to tell InterTalk 
   that no dialtone was found on the current phone number.
   Default: `NO DIAL TONE\'

   VOICE - The number dialled was not answered by a computer.
      Default: '`VOICE\'
   BUSY - The number dialled was engaged.
      Default: `BUSY\'
   RINGING - Waiting for the number dialled to answer.
      Default: `RINGING\'
   RING - An incoming call is being received.
      Default: `RING\'
   DISCONNECT - The modem has disconnected from the line.
      Default: `NO CARRIER\'
   CONNECT - The number you are ringing has been answered and you are 
         now connected to it.
         Default: `CONNECT'
   ERROR - An error has occurred.
      Default: `ERROR\'
   NO ANSWER - The number dialled didn't answer and the modem has 
      timed out waiting for it.
      Default: `NO CARRIER\'

NODELIST DIR - If you use TrapList from TrapDoor Development
  (Maximillian Hantsch & Martin J. Laubach), you can take advantage of 
  the phone number lookup facility by telling InterTalk where you nodelists
  are stored using this item.

PHONE MENU
   This menu offers you various methods to dial a phone number and also
   allows you to the send password related to the currently selected
   phonebook entry.

   PHONEBOOK (Amiga/P or the row of books icon) - Brings up the
      Phonebook for you to modify or use.
      See Advanced Tutorial - Advanced Setup, The Phonebook for a
      complete explanation of the Phonebook.

   DIAL NUMBER (Amiga/N) - Prompts you to enter a phone number which is 
      then dialled by using the Dial-Up Suffix and Prefix strings as 
      specified in the Edit menu.
      See Beginners Tutorial - Using InterTalk, Dialling for information
      on the this item and the Dial Window that occurs when dialling is
      in progress.

   RE-DIAL (Amiga/R) - Redials the last number from the phonebook which 
      you dialled.

   SEND PASSWORD (Amiga/Z) - Send the password associated with the
      currently selected entry in the phonebook to the modem.

SERIAL MENU
   This menu allows to change all aspects of your serial ports 
   configuration.

BAUD-RATE (also FastMenu) - Set your required transmission speed using 
   this sub-menu.

HALF-DUPLEX (also FastMenu) - Toggle between Half and Full Duplex mode. 
   Half duplex is indicated by a tick the left of this menu item.

PARITY - (also FastMenu) - Choose from this sub-menu, the parity
   setting you require.

HANDSHAKE (also FastMenu) - Select your handshaking method.

HANG-UP (Amiga/H) - Using the method specified in the `Hang-Up option' 
   item below, hang up the phone line.

HANG-UP OPTION (also FastMenu) - Designate which 'hang up' mode to use. 
Either `Drop DTR' (the default) or `Send hangup string' which sends the 
string specified in the `Hang-up string' item of the `Edit' menu.

SEND BREAK - Send a break signal to the modem.

IGNORE CD (also FastMenu) - Toggle between ignoring the Carrier Detect 
   line and monitoring it.

TERMINAL MENU
   This menu controls how InterTalk will react to data typed by you and 
   data received from a remote computer.

EMULATION (also FastMenu) - Select which terminal emulation to use will, 
   depending on the computer you are talking to, affect how data is 
   displayed on the screen.
   See Advanced Setup - Terminal Setup, Emulations for more information.

FONT (also FastMenu) - Use this sub-menu to select the font used in the 
   Terminal Window. You can select either of the Amiga's built in ROM 
   fonts ('Topaz 8' or 'Topaz 9') or any disk font you happen to own.
   The default is to use the special InterTalk 8 point font which 
   contains special IBM PC graphic characters and symbols.
   See Advanced Setup - Terminal Setup, Fonts for more information on fonts.

LOAD KEYMAP (Amiga/K or FastMenu) - Load a new keymap. The keymap affects 
   what character is displayed on the screen when a specific key is pressed.
   See your Amiga documentation and Advanced Tutorial - Advanced
   Setup, Terminal Setup - Keymaps for more information.

LOAD F-KEYS (also FastMenu) - Load a new function key definition file.
   See Advanced Tutorial - Advanced Setup, Customizing the Keyboard - 
   Creating a F-Keys file for more information of defining your function 
   keys.

TRANSLATE CR (also FastMenu) - Define what happens when you press the 
   return key in the Terminal Window.
   See Advanced Tutorial - Advanced Setup - Carriage Return Translation
   for more information on the return key.

SWAP DEL & BS (also FastMenu) - Swap the functions of the backspace
   key (delete the character to the left of the cursor) and the delete key
   (delete the character underneath the cursor).
 
DESTRUCTIVE BS (also FastMenu) - When this active (signalled by a tick to 
   the left of the menu item) the backspace key (or delete key if 'Swap
   DEL & BS' is activated) will delete the character to the left of the 
   cursor. Otherwise, it will just move the cursor to the left by one 
   character.

FILE TRANSFER MENU
   From this menu, all aspects of file transmission may be modified, from 
   the file paths which files are sent to and from to the protocols used 
   to send these files.

SEND FILE (Amiga/U) - Effect a file 'upload'. After selecting a file via 
   the Disk Operations Window, the file is transmitted to the remote 
   computer using the protocol specified in the other items of the 
   'File Transfer' menu.

RECEIVE FILE (Amiga/D) - Effect a file 'download'. After requesting that 
   the remote computer you are connected too sends you a file, selecting
   this option will start InterTalk receiving the file using the current 
   protocol and its settings. If you are using ZModem with Auto Downloading
   activated, then option will by selected for you when the file transfer 
   starts.

PROTOCOL (also FastMenu) - From this sub-menu you can select which file 
   transfer protocol you wish to use. 
   See Advanced Tutorial  - Upload and Download option for more 
   information on the protocols and their associated options.

ASCII OPTIONS (also FastMenu)

EXPAND BLANKS - xxx

RECEIVE PATH - Set the path where ASCII downloads will be stored.

SEND PATH - Set the path where ASCII uploads will be sent from.

ZMODEM OPTIONS (also FastMenu)

   The first three options pertain the ZModem file protection
   mode. These three items are mutually exclusive, that is to
   say one and only one may be selected.
   PROTECT FILE - Set ZModem file protection to 'Protect' mode. 
      This stops files being overwritten when downloading.
   APPEND FILE -  Set ZModem file protection to 'Append' mode. 
      This allows interrupted file transfers to be continued from 
      the point of interruption.
   REPLACE FILE - Or no protection. Files of the same name are 
      replaced when downloaded.
   The next two options are also mutually exclusive and define the 
   type of error checking.
   32 BIT CRC - The most secure, but slightly slower form of error checking.
   16 BIT CRC - Slightly less secure than 32 bit CRC, but a little bit 
      faster to effect.

AUTO DWL - When activated (denoted by a tick to the left the item), 
   ZModem Auto Downloading is activated.

FILE PATHS - Use this sub-menu to set the `Send' and `Receive' file paths 
   used by the XModem, YModem and ZModem file transfer protocols.
   See Advanced Setup - Upload and Download Options, Zmodem Options
   for a more detailed description of the effect of these options.
   See Beginners Tutorial - Sending/Receiving Files for more information 
   on file paths.

SPECIAL MENU
   This menu mostly contains options pertaining to modifying purely
   aesthetic features of InterTalk.

OPEN/CLOSE WORKBENCH - If you have enough memory, the Workbench screen 
   can be open at the same time as InterTalk. Although both screens 
   cannot be active at the same time, you can switch back and forwards 
   between them using the depth gadget at the top right corner of each 
   screen. If, you find yourself running short of memory, this option 
   can be used to close the Workbench. Subsequently, if you find that 
   you need to access the Workbench this option can be used to re¬open 
   it.
   
BITPLANES (all the colours gadget in the FastMenu)  - This toggles 
   between two (1 bitplane), four (2 bitplane), eight (3 bitplane) and 
   sixteen (4 bitplane) colour display mode. If selected, a check mark 
   appears beside the menu option. 

PALETTE - Allows you to customise the screen colours to your own 
   preferences. When you select this option, a requester will appear 
   containing the four possible colours used by InterWord, above which 
   are three RGB (red, green, blue), sliders that you can use to change 
   them. A quick glance around the screen will indicate which colours 
   are used for which part of the display. To change a colour, click on 
   the appropriately coloured box at the bottom of the Palette requester, 
   and that colour should appear in the current colour box at the left 
   of the requester. Using the RGB sliders, you can now alter the colour 
   to any of the 4096 colours that the Amiga is capable of displaying. 
   When you are happy with your selection, click OK, and the new palette 
   will be used. If you change your mind about any alterations, provided 
   you haven't already left the Palette requester, you can click Reset 
   to restore the colours to the way they were before you started changing 
   them.

SCREEN SIZE (also FastMenu) - The two options in this sub-menu allow you 
   to modify the width and height of InterTalks screen. If you try to use 
   size not supported by either your screen or monitor you may get some 
   strange effects. 

BORDER (also FastMenu) - This toggle turns the border around the Terminal 
   Window on or off.

INTERLACE TOGGLE - Switches from medium resolution to interlaced screen 
   display mode. This lets you see more text on the screen at a time, 
   but unless you have a flicker fixer or high persistence/multi-sync 
   monitor, the screen will appear to flicker, and may be unpleasant on 
   your eyes with prolonged use.

@ENDNODE

