AMIGA EDITING KEYS
   Keypress                  Function

   Left or Right             Move the cursor one character left or
                             right.

   Shift/Left or Right       Move cursor to the beginning or end of the
                             current string.

   Delete Key                Delete the character under the cursor.

   Backspace Key             Delete the character to the left of the
                             cursor.

   Right Amiga/Q             Undo the last editing change to the string.

   Right Amigaa/X            Delete the whole string.

@endnode


@NODE "APPENDIX C" "Glossary"

ANSI - xxx

ASCII - The 'American Standard Code for Information Interchange'. ASCII
   codes are numerical values for characters. Each character is assigned 
   a numerical value; for example, the letter 'A' has an ASCII decimal 
   value of 65, while lowercase 'a' has a value of 97. All printable 
   characters have a value, also there are values for some special 
   characters that you would not usual see on screen. 

Baud Rate - Effectively, baud rate measures the speed of transmission. A 
   rate of 300 indicates that 300 'bits-per-second' (bps) can be 
   transmitted. In general it takes 10 bits to transmit a single character 
   of data (one start bit, eight data bits and one stop bit), thus 300 
   baud comes at a 30 characters per second, therefore the higher the baud 
   rate, the fast the transmission speed and the less time spent to 
   transfer data.

Bit - A bit is single piece of information. It can be either true or false. 
   Eight bits make a byte which represents a value between 0-255.

BPS - Bits Per Second.

Capture - See File Capture

Carriage Return - Decimal character 13, used by the Amiga to send the cursor
   the beginning of the next line.

Checksum - A method of checking data integrity. The checksum is a value
   which is the result of calculations upon the data. Therefore if the 
   data is changed or corrupted, the checksum will be wrong.

Clipboard - Part of the Amiga's Operating System, the clipboard allows 
   programs which support it to exchange data. The file 'clipboard.device'
   must exists in the 'DEVS:' directory of your boot disk for this 
   function to work.

CPS - Characters Per Second.

Cycle Gadget - A type of gadget which contains a list of options. Only one 
   option is available at any one time. Every time the gadget is selected 
   the next item in the list is presented.
 
Data Bit - The number of bits used to actually transmit data. Seven data 
   bits can represent any value between 0-127, where as eight can represent 
   any value between 0-255.

Depth Gadget - In the top right hand corner of the screen is a small square 
   gadget. Clicking on this gadget will send the screen to the back of all 
   other screens. Nearly all Amiga screens will have a depth gadget.

Dial Window - An InterTalk window which displays the status of the current 
   dial attempt.

DIP Switches  - Little switches which allow you to modify the default 
   configuration of your modem.

Disk Operations Window - A window which allows you to carry out commonly
   used AmigaDOS functions such as rename and delete a file.

Downloading - The process of receiving a file from another computer.

Duplex - The main use of Duplexing is indicate which computer (yours or 
   the remote you are linked to) echoes the characters you type. At Full 
   Duplex any characters you type are sent to the remote which then 'echoes' 
   them back to your screen. On the other hand, Half Duplex tells InterTalk 
   to echo anything you type to the screen.

Echoing - The function of repeating data, typed in by you for example, to 
   the screen.

FastMenu - A large window which allows you to modify most of InterTalks
   settings without having to wade through several menus.

Function keys - The row of ten keys labelled F1-F10 at the top of your
   Amiga keyboard.

F-Keys or Function Keys definition file - A file which contains
   assignments for you function keys.

File Capture - Sometimes known as file logging, this is the function of
   copying all data in the Terminal Window to a file.

File Display List - A list of files displayed in the Disk Operations
   Window.

File Transfer Window - An InterTalk Window which displays the status of a
   file transfer in progress.

Handshaking - Sometimes known as flow control, handshaking control the
   pace of the transfer of data. The types of handshaking are Hardware
   (RTS/CTS) and Software (XON/OFF).

Hangup - Hangup the phone line. This is usually accomplished by the modem
   dropping the DTR (Data Terminal Ready line).

Hayes - A modem standard. Many modern modems use the Hayes command 
   language (also known as ther AT command language). InterTalk is 
   configured, by default, to use this standard.

Icon - A small pictorial representation of a function.

Icon Control Bar - A row of icons at the top of InterTalk's screen
   containing icons relating some of InterTalk's more commonly used
   functions.

InterTalk.CFG - InterTalk's default configuration and settings file. This
   file automatically read when InterTalk is first started.

InterTalk.capt - The default file capture file name.

InterTalk.keys - The default function key definition file. If copy exists
   in the directory from which you start InterTalk it is read in
   automatically.

InterTalk.phone - The default phonebook file. If copy exists in the
   directory from which you start InterTalk it is read in automatically.

InterWord - Interactivision's Word Processing package.

Linefeed - Decimal character 10. Used to move down one line.

Main Status Bar - At the very top of InterTalk's screen this bar displays
   which version of InterTalk you are using and the amount of free RAM
   available.

Modem - MOdulator DEModulator, A device for sending data over telephone
   lines.

Parity - A simple method of checking that data sent was received correctly. 

Phonebook - A list of phone numbers and the settings used when calling
   these phone numbers.

Phonebook Edit Window - Phonebook entries can be created and modified
   from this window. Accessed from either the Create or Edit gadgets in 
   the Phonebook List Window.

Phonebook List Window - The Phonebook's control window from which entries
   can be deleted, dialed, edited and created.

Protocol - A method of transmitting data. Most file transfer protocol 
   incorporate some form of error checking to ensure data integrity. See
   XModem, YModem and ZModem.

Pulse Dialling - A method that telephone exchanges use to dial phone 
   numbers, a number of clicks or pulses (the number being the number
   dialled) are sent. Outdated now by the faster Tone Dialling.

Quick Status Box - To the right of the Icon Control Bar, this box
   contains data which tells you at a glance the current settings which
   InterTalk is using.

RAM - Random Access Memory. A volatile storage media used by computers
   to store programs and data currently in use.

RTS/CTS - Hardware handshaking. A way of controling the flow of data between
   two computers. Also see XON/XOFF.

Scrollback Buffer - An area of memory which stores any recent activity in
   the Terminal Window. This area can be viewed using the Scrollback 
   Window.

Scrollback Window - Used to display the contents of the Scrollback Buffer.

Serial.Device - Part of the Amiga operating system, used to control the
   serial port.

Start and Stop Bits - To ensure that each byte transmitted is correct a
   low voltage signal is sent to mark the beginning and end of the byte.

Stop Bit - See Start and Stop Bits

Terminal Window - Sometimes refereed to as a Dumb Terminal this is the
   area where you can type commands which are sent directly to the modem
   and thus down the phone lines and to the remote computer at the other 
   end.

Tone Dialling - A modern method of dialling. A different to tone is used
   to represent each number. Much faster than the old Pulse Dialling 
   method.

Uploading - The process of sending a file to a remote computer.

Workbench - The Amiga's Graphical User Interface (GUI).

XModem - One of the earliest protocols, Ward Christensen developed the
   public domain '8-bit' error checking protocol XModem. It is a single 
   file protocol (each file must transmitted individually) which uses a 
   128 byte data block and half duplex mode. 

   InterTalk supports to other forms of XModem, XModem-CRC which forces 
   the use of CRC error checking (standard XModem tries to use CRC and 
   if that fails switches checksum error checking) and XModem-1K which 
   uses CRC error checking and a one kilobyte (1024 bytes) block size.

XON/XOFF - Also know as software handshaking or software flow control. By
   sending an XOFF signal the transmitting computer is told to pause it's
   data transmission until it receives and XON signal. This is used for 
   example, while the receiving computer writes to disk.

YModem - Is the same as XModem-1K except it allows multiple file transfers. 
   YModem-G is a variation on YModem except it doesn't support error 
   checking and expects your modem to provide this service. The YModem-G 
   protocol should only be used with modems which support error checking.

ZModem - Used on many modern services, ZModem is a very efficient 
   protocol. Featuring auto downloading it can also restart and interrupted
   file transfer.

@Endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX D" "Installing"

INTERTALK TO YOUR HARD DISK

Installing InterTalk to your hard disk is simplicity itself. 
First create a new drawer on your hard drive where you want InterTalk to
be stored. Do this by 'duplicating' the 'Empty' drawer (or, under
Workbench 2.0 selecting the 'New Drawer' item from the 'Window' menu).
Click on the your new drawers icon and while holding the Shift key down 
double-click on the HDInstall icon. After a few minutes InterTalk will 
be ready to use from your hard disk.

@endnode

